<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Body length: male 7.5-9.5 mm, female 9.5-10 mm. The conspicuous golden pile on tergite 4 places this species in the 
<taxonomicName lsidName="flavofascium" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="flavofascium">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">flavofascium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. Within this group, this species is distinguished by the combination of the following characters: basoflagellomere longer than scape, postpronotum bare, wing cell c bare on posterobasal 1/4 or less, alula largely bare, wing cell r4+5 partly yellow. Male genitalia as in 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 280–283" captionStartId="F48" captionText="Figures 280 - 283. Male genitalia of Peradon species 280 P. brevis holotype 281 P. chrysopygus Costa Rica RMNH 282 P. ballux holotype 283 P. aurigaster Bolivia RMNH." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures280-283" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362318" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures280-283">Fig. 283</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
A Brazilian female specimen from the USNM collection carries a red label stating 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“Paratype”">&quot;Paratype&quot;</normalizedToken>
(see Additional specimens). As 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1155/1941/46264" author="Hull, FM" journalOrPublisher="Psyche" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="149 - 165" refId="B11" refString="Hull, FM, 1941. Descriptions of some new species of Syrphidae. Psyche 48: 149 - 165" title="Descriptions of some new species of Syrphidae." url="https://doi.org/10.1155/1941/46264" volume="48" year="1941">Hull (1941)</bibRefCitation>
based his description on a single specimen and does not mention additional material, this specimen cannot be considered a paratype. Variation in colouration in this species is considerable. Based on the present material, it is not possible to assess the taxonomic relevance of this variability, but it seems possible that 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. aurigaster" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aurigaster">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. aurigaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as defined here represents a species complex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
